  Hi, I'm a huge fan of GraalVM's usage of partial evaluation (Futamura projections) for cross-platform compilation, but I have never tried to use it for anything serious, so I really don't know anything about this.
  
  By the looks of things though, the Graal runtime does not compile the Java module system into the final binary (it may just resolve modules and classes at compiletime), and/or has limitations on reflection, as you point out.
  
  The reason ClassGraph uses reflection to call `ModuleReader` (via `ModuleReaderProxy`) is that ClassGraph is built for JDK 7, for maximum compatibility. I have considered raising the minimum JDK version to 11 or even 17 for ClassGraph 5.0 (although I don't have time to work on that right now). But part of that change could be to drop `ModuleReaderProxy` and just use `ModuleReader` (which was introduced in JDK 9) directly.
  
  What I wrote in the docs is that to support Java environments that are non-standard (like Android, or GraalVM), you should do your scanning at build-time:
  
  https://github.com/classgraph/classgraph/wiki/Build-Time-Scanning
